name: differences in amount of elastic light scattering
negative staining
definition: visualization by exclusion of a stain in which the specimen is immersed; compare with "positive staining.

name: macroscopy
definition: methods for imaging objects large enough to be observed by the unaided eye

name: dark-field microscopy
definition: imaging with rejection of the unscattered illumination (removal of the zero order component of the diffracted wave)

name: unprocessed raw data
definition: data as acquired, with no alterations that change the pixel values.

name: spinning disk scanning
definition: scanning by multiple points of light arising from pinholes in a spinning disk that is illuminated by a widefield source

name: fluorescent label
parent: vizualization of label conjugated to probe

name: FRET
definition: Fluorescence (or Forster) resonance energy transfer; a method of estimating the distance between two fluorophores by measuring the extent of non-radiative energy transfer between the two. Experimentally, this involves selective excitation of one while observing emission from the other.

name: secondary electron generation
definition: electrons generated by inelastic scattering of other radiation, the primary radiation.

name: tissue in vitreous ice embedment
definition: Fully hydrated tissue rapidly frozen to produce vitrified water, and maintained continuously below the glass transition temperature of water (approximately -137 deg C

name: process
definition: An occurrent that has temporal proper parts and for some time t, p s-depends_on some material entity at t.

name: imaged parameter
definition: The physical property of the specimen that leads to the modifications of the illumination that are recorded in the image.

name: recorded image
definition: methods and devices used for capturing an image of a real object; distinct from images created by artwork

name: Blue fluorescent protein from Aequorea victoria
parent: fluorescent protein derived from Aequorea victoria

name: Rheinberg illumination
definition: illumination at angles less than the acceptance angle of the image-forming lens is attenuated by a filter to give a colored background of unscattered light; higher angle illumination may be filtered to give a contrasting color

name: critical_point dried specimen
definition: specimen from which water has been removed by a process that avoids liquid-gas and solid-gas phase transitions.

name: ANSOM
definition: Aperture-less NSOM.

name: SPIM
definition: single (or selective) plane illumination.

name: resolution-enhancing method
definition: methods for increasing the resolution beyond the classical Abbe diffraction limit

name: visualization by chemical attribute
definition: methods of visualization that differentiate regions of the specimen on the basis of their chemical properties

name: intracellular filling
definition: visualization of the connected regions of a cell by filling with a label

name: TexasRed
definition: fluorophore with ex/em 589/615

name: differences in adsorption or binding of stain
focussed ion beam scanning electron microscopy (FIB-SEM)
definition: A method of reconstructing 3D structure by combining focussed ion beam milling to remove sucessive layers from a sample block with scanning EM to image the exposed surface between each milling step.

name: shadowing and plating
definition: visualization by depositing a label on the surface of a specimen uniformly (plating), or from a particular direction so that surface topography becomes visible (shadowing)

name: enzyme label
parent: vizualization of label conjugated to probe

name: fluorescent protein derived from Aequorea victoria
widefield illumination
definition: illumination that covers the entire field of view of the image-forming lens

name: living tissue
definition: Unfixed fully hydrated tissue, typically employed to monitor dynamic changes in the living state.

name: anaxial illumination
definition: Illumination is distributed asymmetrically around the optic axis, typically achieved by a non-circular stop placed below the lower lens element and aperture of the condenser.

name: modified objective lens
definition: Uses an objective with extra components to manipulate the wave front in the plane of the objective aperture.

name: darkfield illumination
definition: illumination restricted to angles that exceed the acceptance angle of the image-forming lens

name: AzuriteFP
parent: Blue fluorescent protein from Aequorea victoria

name: X-Rhodamine
definition: fluorophore derivative of rhodamine with ex/em 580/605

name: hollow-cone illumination
definition: illumination parallel or at small angles to the optical axis is attenuated or blocked by a stop

name: scanning probe microscopy
definition: imaging by means of a physical probe that passes over the sample

name: single point scanning
definition: illumination by a single spot of light that is scanned across the field of view

name: X-ray radiography
definition: Radiography using X-rays

name: detection method
definition: media and devices employed for recording the alterations in the illumination that result from its interaction with the sample

name: serial block face SEM (SBFSEM)
definition: A method of reconstructing 3D structure by combining serial sectioning with scanning EM.

name: slit-scan confocal microscopy
definition: illumination and detection via a thin slit

name: Wollaston prism
definition: a birefringent optical element typically used to split polarized illumination into two sets of parallel but displaced rays

name: narrowfield illumination
definition: illumination restricted to a small portion of the field of view of the imaging lens; often one or more diffraction limited spots

name: Tetramethyl rhodamine (TRITC)
definition: fluorophore derivative of rhodamine with ex/em 547/572

name: CARS
definition: coherent Raman anti-Stokes microscopy

name: SiriusFP
parent: Blue fluorescent protein from Aequorea victoria

name: array-scan confocal microscopy
definition: Fixed array of sources focused to an array of spots that is swept over the specimen in raster fashion

name: occurrent
definition: An entity that has temporal parts and that happens, unfolds or develops through time.

name: independent continuant
definition: A continuant that is a bearer of quality and realizable entity entities, in which other entities inhere and which itself cannot inhere in anything.

name: pulsed illumination
definition: illumination that varies with time; often achieved with pulsed lasers for the purpose of generating very-high peak illumination power

name: boundaries between regions with different refractive index
permeabilized tissue
definition: Tissue treated to make cell membranes permeable, typically for the purpose of allowing access by exogenous stains or substrates.

name: visualization of contiguous regions
definition: methods of visualization that differentiate between different regions or surfaces of the specimen based on contiguity

name: multiple point scanning
definition: illumination by multiple points of light simultaneously

name: OCT
definition: optical coherence tomography; an interferometric method of imaging using back-scattered photons (elastic scattering)

name: PAINT (point accumulation for imaging in nanoscale topography)
EBFP
parent: Blue fluorescent protein from Aequorea victoria

name: X-ray tomography
definition: Tomography using X-ray illumination.

name: lyophilized specimen
definition: specimen from which water has been removed by evaporation under vacuum at a temperature below freezing.

name: computed tomography
definition: Tomography in which virtual sections are taken from multiple angles and the results are processed via tomographic reconstruction software to produce 2 or 3D images.

name: atomic force microscopy
definition: the scanning probe is maintained at a fixed distance above the surface e of the specimen by van der Waals forces

name: FLIP
definition: Fluorescence loss in photobleaching; a method of determining whether two populations of fluorophore are in diffusive communication with one another by observing the decrease in brightness of one population when the other population is subjected to continuous photobleaching.

name: differences in deposition of metal shadow
array scanning
definition: Multiple points of illumination generated by a fixed array of sources.

name: radiography
definition: An imaging technique that uses high energy electromagnetic radiation, typically X-rays, as a source of illumination.

name: detection of current induced in the specimen
secondary_electron imaging
definition: image created using the electrons generated by ionization of a sample due to inelastic scattering of the primary beam of radiation

name: solvent permeabilized
definition: permeabilization due to extraction of lipid from membranes by an organic solvent such as acetone or methanol.

name: electron dense label
parent: vizualization of label conjugated to probe

name: FRAP
definition: Fluorescence loss in photobleaching; a method of determining the rate and extent of exchange between a localized population of fluorophore and a non-localized diffusible pool, by observing the rate of recovery of brightness of the localized population after photobleaching.

name: Cyan fluorescent protein from Aequorea
parent: fluorescent protein derived from Aequorea victoria

name: specimen_modifying_illumination
definition: Illumination used for the purpose of inducing some observable change in the specimen during the course of an imaging session. This illumination may or may not be the same as the illumination used for imaging. Typically used in conjunction with live-cell imaging

name: glycerol permeabilized
definition: tissue made permeable by the action of glycerol

name: saturated structured-illumination microscopy (SSIM)
definition: structured illumination used at sufficiently high power to cause significant ground-state depletion of the imaged fluorophore, thus allowing for non-linear resolution enhancement

name: Yellow fluorescent protein from Aequorea
parent: fluorescent protein derived from Aequorea victoria

name: material entity
definition: An independent continuant that is spatially extended whose identity is independent of that of other entities and can be maintained through time.

name: distribution of a specific nucleic acid sequence
tomography
definition: An imaging technique that creates virtual sections through the use of any kind of penetrating wave.

name: vizualization of label conjugated to probe
continuant
definition: An entity that exists in full at any time in which it exists at all, persists through time while maintaining its identity and has no temporal parts.

name: animation
definition: A form of graphical illustration that changes with time to give a sense of motion or represent dynamic changes in the portrayal.

name: slit-scanning illumination
definition: illumination in the shape of a thin line that is swept over the field of view

name: non-linear method
definition: computational method that are mathematically non-linear; image intensity is not conserved, and the data are in general not suitable for quantitative analyses of pixel values

name: detergent permeabilized
definition: Membrane permeabilization by the action of ionic or non-ionic detergents

name: fluorescence polarization (polarization angle resolved fluorescence emission)
scanning electron microscopy (SEM)
definition: image is formed by scanning the surface of the specimen with a beam of electrons in a raster pattern

name: Green fluorescent protein from Aequorea
parent: fluorescent protein derived from Aequorea victoria

name: FIONA (fluorescence imaging with one nanometer accuracy)
back-scattered_electron imaging
definition: imaged formed using electrons undergoing elastic scattering at very high angles, with emission of characteristic X-rays

name: portrayed image
definition: methods and devices used for creating images by some form of artwork, as distinct from capturing images by means of some recording device

name: saponin permeabilized
definition: Saponin, a detergent-like molecule, preferentially forms holes in membranes that contain cholesterol.

name: primary antibody plus labeled secondary antibody
isolated subcellular component
definition: A fragment of a cell, subcellular organelle, or macromolecular complex.

name: eosin
definition: Staining with an aqueous or alcoholic solution of eosin Y,colors eosinophilic structures in various shades of red, pink and orange. The eosinophilic structures are generally composed of intracellular or extracellular protein. The Lewy bodies and Mallory bodies are examples of eosinophilic structures. Most of the cytoplasm is eosinophilic. Red blood cells are stained intensely red.

name: linear method
definition: a computational method that is linear in the mathematical sense, meaning that image intensity is conserved and the data remain suitable for all quantitative analyses

name: source of contrast
definition: The source of the variation in the imaged parameter across the field of view.

name: hematoxylin
definition: The staining method involves application of hemalum, which is a complex formed from aluminium ions and oxidized haematoxylin. This colors nuclei of cells (and a few other objects, such as keratohyalin granules) blue. The staining of nuclei by hemalum does not require the presence of DNA and is probably due to binding of the dye-metal complex to arginine-rich basic nucleoproteins such as histones. The mechanism is different from that of nuclear staining by basic (cationic) dyes such as thionine or toluidine blue. Staining by basic dyes is prevented by chemical or enzymatic extraction of nucleic acids. Such extractions do not prevent staining of nuclei by hemalum.

name: light-sheet illumination
definition: illumination in the form of a thin sheet of light directed perpendicular to the optic axis

name: illumination method
definition: sources and methods for illumination

name: microscopy
definition: methods for forming images of objects too small to be observed with the unaided eye
